<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-721-900  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 721 900.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 2 1989 v23 n40 pS22(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Food fight: business strategies. (includes related article onin-store computer systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Von Simpson, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Automation and the integration of information systems plays acrucial role in the competitive fast-food restaurant industry.andO;Burger King is integrating microcomputers into its Point-of-Sale(POS) systems in 1990.andP;  IBM and NCR technology will give branchmanagers access to information stored on the corporate mainframe.andO;Other vendors, McDonald's Corp, Kentucky Fried Chicken Corp andWendy's, for example, are all launching automation projects.andP;  Thecentral focus of these projects is to lower costs and increaseboth customer service and profitability through the automation ofaccounting, labor management and cash flow functions.andP;  Pizza HutInc plans to reduce its labor costs from 25 cents on the dollar to21 cents on the dollar by computerized labor schedulingapplications.andP;  Increasingly, the microcomputer will not be a meresupport device, but a crucial information resource managementtool.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CompetitionPOS SystemsVendorsInformation Resource ManagementIntegrated SystemsRestaurant Business.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>